Layer-1

Is Ethereum Good?

Kunal Goel
Seth Bloomberg
Kinji Steimetz

Aug 23, 2024   8 min read

Primer


Ethereum pivoted to a Layer-2 (L2) scaling roadmap in 2020 from its original execution sharding plan. In the L2 scaling roadmap, Ethereum delegates transaction execution to a myriad of L2s but provides them data availability which ensures a high degree of security. Currently, Ethereum provides data availability through proto-danksharding (6 data blobs) and will eventually enable danksharding (64 blobs).

This roadmap has been highly successful. Rollups now account for 87% of daily transactions, which is 6+ times of the Ethereum mainnet. L2 transactions typically cost less than a cent allowing growth in users and use cases. Vitalik Buterin even argues that the L2 design is not dissimilar to execution sharding. Instead, it is even better because it allows for more experimentation in design without overloading Ethereums consensus.

However, critics argue that Layer-2s are value extractive. The argument is that execution and transaction ordering (MEV) generate the most value in the crypto stack, and data is commoditized. As such, L2s retain most of the value, not Ethereum, in this rollup-centric scaling framework.

The critics further point to the fact that Ethereums gas fee is the lowest its been in many years even as we are in a ~bull market. It is no longer ultra sound money as inflation exceeds burn. Further, they argue that there will be no economic incentive to decentralize the sequencer as it is profitable to keep it centralized. Even further, if a Layer-2 were to build a strong network, it would move off Ethereum so as not to pay rent.

Ethereums recent underperformance against Bitcoin and Solana has validated the critics' views. But price tends to lead the narrative, and we want to lead both. So, is Ethereum good and strong, or is it the LTC of this cycle?

The argument perhaps boils down to the following unsettled questions -

  1. What drives the value of a Layer-1 native asset? If it is execution, then ETH leaks value, if it is something else, then it may not.
  2. Are Layer-2 incentives separate from the Layer-1? Do L2s receive enough value from the L1 to remain aligned?
  3. Will successful L2s eventually leave the base layer?
  4. Finally, is Ethereum good, or is its underperformance indicative of greater fundamental problems?

Seth

Watching ETH underperform BTC and SOL on a YTD basis has been tough for ETH holders. Layered on top of the underperformance is the drastic drop in direct fee value capture due to introducing data blobs with EIP-4844. Perhaps most important, for some, is the migration of general economic activity from the Ethereum mainnet to a growing set of L2s. This has led to some hand-wringing and broader concerns over what Ethereum should focus on developing and what the future of ETH, the asset, looks like.

In short, in my view, Ethereum is good.

First and foremost, it is the oldest, most successful smart contract platform to date. A strong, robust community has emerged through its history of monumental upgrades (e.g., The Merge) and various ups and downs along the way. The notion of community is one of the key differentiators among L1s, and its not something that can be built overnight. There is no denying the robustness of the Ethereum community.

The revolving debate around whether or not L2s are extensions of Ethereum seems to once again be the flavor of the month. But, whats not up for debate is ETHs dominance within DeFi across the largest L2s. For example, consider Aave, which is the largest lending protocol across Arbitrum, Base, and Optimism:

  • ArbitrumETH and ETH-based derivatives account for over 50% of the supplied assets, represent 3 of the top 5 markets, and total nearly $590M in value.
  • BaseETH and ETH-based derivatives account for over 80% of the supplied assets, represent 4 of the top 5 markets, and total nearly $140M in value.
  • OptimismETH and ETH-based derivatives account for nearly 50% of the supplied assets, represent 2 of the top 5 markets, and total nearly $110M in value.

The point here is that the ubiquity of ETH across these L2s is a good thing for the asset as it drives demand for it and the adjacent protocols issuing the derivative tokens. At scale, if Ethereum is successful, L2s will serve as economic grounds, and ETH will be collateral and, more generally, a highly leveraged and in-demand asset.

In the meantime, until the price action swings back in favor of ETH (looking at you ETH ETF flows), the debate and existential concerns regarding Ethereum's future will continue.

Kinji

In my view, Ethereum's rollup-centric approach does not significantly add value to ETH as an asset, mainly because Ethereum lacks a way to ensure rollups stay aligned with the base layer. Before diving deeper, it's important to distinguish the potential value drivers for ETH. Two main views exist on what drives ETH's value. One sees ETH's value coming from the cash flows paid to the network in transactions and MEV fees. The other view is that ETH derives its value from a monetary premium, functioning as a gas token, medium of exchange, and collateral asset.

Focusing on the first view, where ETH gains value from cash flows, Ethereum operates like a business selling block space. Before rollups, Ethereum sold block space directly to users, who paid ETH for transaction fees. However, during the 2021 bull market, rising gas fees hindered growth by pricing out many users. In response, Ethereum adopted a rollup-centric strategy, similar to partnering with intermediaries who use block space more efficiently, introducing L2s, which buy Ethereum block space and sell it to users at lower costs. As a result, growth in base-layer transactions has slowed as users move to cheaper L2s, meaning Ethereum captures a smaller share of onchain transaction fees. Conceptually, rollups are a long-term strategy where many L2s would drive more users and fees back to Ethereum. Ideally, this would allow Ethereum to collect higher fees from a wider user base. However, the strategy is risky because Ethereum cannot enforce alignment between the base layer and rollups. Optimists argue that Ethereums network effects, like liquidity and user experience, will keep L2s in its ecosystem. However, I believe L2s could develop their network effects, allowing them to spin off into standalone chains, and eliminating their need to pay fees to Ethereum. In this scenario, the rollup strategy could backfire, with the most successful rollups becoming independent and no longer contributing fees to Ethereum. If this happens, Ethereum could face lower value accrual in the near term as transaction activity moves off the base layer, along with a longer-term risk that future revenue driversL2swont remain customers of Ethereum.

The second view, which treats ETH as a form of money, faces similar risks but with less immediate impact. Most L2s currently use ETH as their gas token, allowing ETH to maintain its monetary premium as a gas token, medium of exchange, and collateral asset, even as transactions shift off the base layer. However, the long-term risk remains: successful rollups could eventually launch their chains with native tokens for gas, reducing ETH's monetary premium.

In summary, the rollup strategy relies on L2s remaining loyal customers, which creates uncertainty and long-term risks for ETH's value accrual. To mitigate this, Ethereum could focus on attracting users back to the base layer by improving L1 and reducing its reliance on rollups for value. Another option is to create a mechanism ensuring rollups stay committed to the L1, guaranteeing they drive value to ETH.

Kunal

The questions asked above are unsettled. However, as a full-time analyst, I present my views on these unsettled questions.

Value Drivers for an L1 Native Asset:

I have proposed that if the price of the native asset drives the supply of security, then the demand for security must drive the value of the L1 asset. The drivers for demand for security, in turn, are the largest applications and users on the network.

The largest intrinsic source of security demand is the native asset itself, as money. And the largest extrinsic sources of security demand are large entities like Layer-2s, stablecoins, and DeFi apps.

With this framework, L2s add value to the native asset. They increase the moneyness of the L1 native asset by making it more accessible. Additionally, as they grow, they require a higher security guarantee from the base layer and, as such, drive value to the token.

Using MEV or execution as a valuation model misses the forest for the trees. The present value of all future MEV may provide a floor to the value of these assets. However, it misses the nuance that significant research efforts are going into MEV minimization. Blockchains may be asset ledgers, but their native assets are more than just equity for them.

L2s Alignment:

L2s receive significant value from Ethereum and, as such, are unlikely to leave.

  • Using Ethereum for DA allows for a trust-minimized bridge that drives their onchain economy. As Seth notes above, there is a large amount of ETH as TVL in L2 DeFi applications. Users may not have bridged as much if there were additional trust guarantees.
  • Sharing Ethereum as the common DA layer allows for the flow of value between L2s. In such a free-flowing economy, the sum may be greater than the parts.

Additionally, since Ethereum-based L2s have open-source and similar designs, they have limited bargaining power over the L1. Even if they were to leave, they would have to risk losing Ethereum-aligned users and their capital to a similar L2 that remains aligned.

Is Ethereum Good?

Ethereum is good. The L2 scaling roadmap has worked. After relative outperformance in 2021-22, a period of underperformance is a good reality check. There seems to be a new fire in the Ethereum camp with scaling planned for the base layer and even more performant L2s like MegaETH.

Ethereum is good.

Kunal Goel

Kunal previously worked in equity research and now considers himself a financial analyst in crypto. He specializes in valuation and bottom-up analysis for Layer-1 and DeFi protocols because he has yet to learn of a way to value NFTs.

Prior to joining Messari, Seth worked in traditional finance software and services, and has a MSc in Applied Mathematics. Seth is a Senior Research Analyst on the Enterprise Research team, and focuses on infrastructure, verifiable compute, and the AI x Crypto intersection.
